edom.edomvd: On-Street Striped - Part of the roadway and delineated by pavement markings and regulatory signage. The lane which can be shared with in-line skaters, is usually located next to curb lane parking, and may include a marked buffer zone.

On-Street Proposed Route - A proposed on-street bicycle route (no pavement markings) that is recommended for bicycle travel. These routes may become On-Street Striped routes at which point their classification will change

Greenway Paths - Separated from the roadway and delineated by pavement markings and regulatory signage. Bicycle paths are usually shared with multiple users, including pedestrians, runners and skaters. These paths usually follow waterfronts, rail lines, highways and parks

Greenway Connectors/Signed Route - Shared use of the roadway, typically designated with informational signs. These routes often connect to greenway paths, but may also serve as a connection between on-street bike lanes.

Planned/Proposed Greenways - A proposed bicycle path separated from the roadway, these paths usually follow waterfronts, rail lines, highways and parks. These routes may become Greenway Paths in the future at which point their classification will change
Signed Route - Shared use of the roadway, typically designated with informational signs.

The maximum width (measured in feet) of the existing bicycle facility at the segment level for existing on-street bike lanes and greenway paths. For greenway connectors and signed routes, the width provided refers to the total street width.

An identification number for a route, attached to groups of segments. A Route is defined as continuous, in both facility type and the street name. The beginning and ending of the route are displayed in the FromStreet and ToStreet columns. There may be a few cases where the segment street name is not continuous, but the FacilityNumber is the same. This will occur in three situations. First, if the street has multiple names assigned to it, for example the names "6 Av" and "Avenue of the Americas" in Manhattan are given to the same street and have the same FacilityNumber. Second, when a street has an East and a West name, for example E 120 St and W 120 St will be considered to be the same street and have the same FacilityNumber. Third, routes that travel through parks may have multiple street names, but because the routes are entirely contained within the park the facility number will be the same.
